with the beta function . At small coupling, the action reduces to the symplectic fermions 
theory, and the partition function () coincides with
the determinant of  the Laplacian with periodic boundary conditions 
in the space direction and antiperiodic boundary conditions in 
the "time" direction (along which the trace is taken). For  negative,
the model flows to weak coupling in the UV, and is massive in the IR, where symmetry is 
restored. The action reads then, in terms of the fermion variables,
and after trivial rescalings,

 

Notice that the relative normalization of the two terms can be
changed at will by changing the normalization of the fermions. The
relative sign can also be changed by switching the fermion labels
. However, the sign of the four fermion term cannot
be changed, and determines whether the model is massive or massless
in the IR. For 
 positive, the model flows (perturbatively) to weak coupling in the IR. This is the
case of the lattice model introduced in. 



